<tt>Tue Nov  4 18:04:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
During the day in Viet Nam you could see the rain coming. Often it would come in from the South China Sea in a Southwest direction, but just as often it came from the An Hoa Mountains in a Northeast direction and you could visibly see the rain creep over the mountains around the sides and into the valley's below. It was like seeing a large sheet of  blueish-gray colored cellophane being unrolled slowly over the mountains range and being laid over the valley's below. Unlike the rest of Viet Nam the monsoon rains in Quan Nam province came twice a year. It rained fast and slow, down and hard, in soft caressing mists and in terrorizing torrents.  The rain was not only wet, cold and heavy, it also had its own sounds and smells, it took on various shapes, intensity and power. <br>
The worst storms we experienced came when the South China Sea winds blew it every which way and there was no where to turn away from the rain. <br>
On the morning of October 8th, 1967, the area we were in, suffered one of the worst typhoons and floods in years. We would be under water for three days. Last year 1996, the area suffered a similar fate, this year according to the following story it was the worst ever.<br>
